1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,240
Here's the whole pitch in one screen.

2
00:00:02,240 --> 00:00:03,980
A minute ago, this referral was missing

3
00:00:03,980 --> 00:00:06,160
a required nephrology lab.

4
00:00:06,160 --> 00:00:08,080
Now it's accepted because the app found

5
00:00:08,080 --> 00:00:11,080
that evidence in the chart attached it to the passport

6
00:00:11,080 --> 00:00:13,840
and resubmitted the packet without starting over.

7
00:00:13,840 --> 00:00:16,280
You can literally see the new UACR row,

8
00:00:16,280 --> 00:00:17,880
the checklist turning complete,

9
00:00:17,880 --> 00:00:19,960
and the intake decision flipping from input

10
00:00:19,960 --> 00:00:21,860
required to accepted.

11
00:00:21,860 --> 00:00:23,580
That's Consult Passport.

12
00:00:23,580 --> 00:00:25,280
It is not an AI note writer.

13
00:00:25,280 --> 00:00:27,400
It is a referral acceptance engine

14
00:00:27,400 --> 00:00:29,240
that makes the rules visible.

15
00:00:29,240 --> 00:00:31,160
Repairs what can be repaired,

16
00:00:31,160 --> 00:00:33,200
and keeps an audit trail of every step

17
00:00:33,200 --> 00:00:35,020
between rejection and readiness.

18
00:00:36,880 --> 00:00:39,800
Most referral workflows break on the boring part.

19
00:00:39,800 --> 00:00:41,520
The packet is almost good enough,

20
00:00:41,520 --> 00:00:44,720
one lab is missing, the specialist desk kicks it back,

21
00:00:44,720 --> 00:00:46,960
and suddenly the team is doing phone calls,

22
00:00:46,960 --> 00:00:49,200
chart scavenger hunts, and status updates

23
00:00:49,200 --> 00:00:51,080
in three different places.

24
00:00:51,080 --> 00:00:53,200
What I like about this product is that it treats

25
00:00:53,200 --> 00:00:55,760
that mess as a real workflow problem.

26
00:00:55,760 --> 00:00:58,640
Instead of asking staff to guess what intake wants,

27
00:00:58,640 --> 00:01:00,680
it makes the requirements explicit,

28
00:01:00,680 --> 00:01:02,160
keeps them attached to the run,

29
00:01:02,160 --> 00:01:04,920
and turns the repair path into part of the product.

30
00:01:06,480 --> 00:01:08,880
The workspace starts with real patient context

31
00:01:08,880 --> 00:01:10,480
instead of a blank form.

32
00:01:10,480 --> 00:01:14,240
For this seeded demo, Eleanor Vance already has CKD history,

33
00:01:14,240 --> 00:01:16,320
recent renal labs, medications,

34
00:01:16,320 --> 00:01:18,360
and a referral note in the chart.

35
00:01:18,360 --> 00:01:20,440
The useful thing is that I do not have to manually

36
00:01:20,440 --> 00:01:22,880
repackage that information before I can even ask

37
00:01:22,880 --> 00:01:24,440
for intake review.

38
00:01:24,440 --> 00:01:26,960
I can open the patient record, skim the evidence

39
00:01:26,960 --> 00:01:28,320
that already exists,

40
00:01:28,320 --> 00:01:31,040
and then start a Consult Passport from there.

41
00:01:31,040 --> 00:01:34,800
Under the hood, the app snapshots the FHIR-style context,

42
00:01:34,800 --> 00:01:36,720
assembles the evidence table,

43
00:01:36,720 --> 00:01:38,800
and prepares a structured referral packet

44
00:01:38,800 --> 00:01:40,960
from the chart that is already on hand.

45
00:01:42,840 --> 00:01:46,240
When I submit, the first decision is intentionally strict.

46
00:01:46,240 --> 00:01:48,200
Intake does not just wave the packet through

47
00:01:48,200 --> 00:01:50,320
because the story sounds reasonable.

48
00:01:50,320 --> 00:01:53,360
It evaluates the actual requirements for this destination,

49
00:01:53,360 --> 00:01:56,320
and it tells me one required item is still missing,

50
00:01:56,360 --> 00:01:58,120
a recent UACR.

51
00:01:58,120 --> 00:01:59,800
That is exactly the kind of detail

52
00:01:59,800 --> 00:02:03,280
that usually disappears into email or verbal follow-up.

53
00:02:03,280 --> 00:02:05,240
Here it is explicit, repairable,

54
00:02:05,240 --> 00:02:07,480
and attached to the same live run.

55
00:02:07,480 --> 00:02:09,560
I can see the checklist, the missing rule,

56
00:02:09,560 --> 00:02:12,000
the decision summary, and the button that tells me

57
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:14,600
there is still a legitimate path to acceptance.

58
00:02:16,480 --> 00:02:19,280
Now watch the part that actually feels different.

59
00:02:19,280 --> 00:02:21,080
I click fetch missing evidence.

60
00:02:21,080 --> 00:02:24,400
The chart tool looks for the latest qualifying UACR,

61
00:02:24,400 --> 00:02:27,520
the run attaches that observation to the evidence table,

62
00:02:27,520 --> 00:02:30,160
and the packet is resubmitted immediately.

63
00:02:30,160 --> 00:02:32,080
There is no fake magic here.

64
00:02:32,080 --> 00:02:34,920
The product is very literal about what changed.

65
00:02:34,920 --> 00:02:38,320
You can see the checklist move from four of five to five of five.

66
00:02:38,320 --> 00:02:41,280
You can see the new UACR row appear in the passport,

67
00:02:41,280 --> 00:02:43,320
and you can see the intake decision flip

68
00:02:43,320 --> 00:02:45,560
to accepted on the same run.

69
00:02:45,560 --> 00:02:48,480
Instead of sending a coordinator on a scavenger hunt,

70
00:02:48,480 --> 00:02:51,600
the system closes the gap with real chart evidence

71
00:02:51,600 --> 00:02:53,960
and shows you the exact before and after.

72
00:02:56,120 --> 00:02:59,240
What makes this more than a flashy demo is the audit trail.

73
00:02:59,240 --> 00:03:02,160
The passport is visible, the evidence is visible,

74
00:03:02,160 --> 00:03:04,040
the intake decision is visible,

75
00:03:04,040 --> 00:03:06,600
and the submission trace shows the exact sequence.

76
00:03:06,600 --> 00:03:09,760
Context bound, snapshot received, packet assembled,

77
00:03:09,760 --> 00:03:13,160
input required, repair started, UACR attached,

78
00:03:13,160 --> 00:03:14,960
resubmitted, accepted.

79
00:03:14,960 --> 00:03:17,920
That matters because referral automation is only useful

80
00:03:17,920 --> 00:03:20,480
if a human can still explain the outcome.

81
00:03:20,480 --> 00:03:22,640
If an intake lead asks why this passed,

82
00:03:22,640 --> 00:03:24,480
there is a concrete answer.

83
00:03:24,480 --> 00:03:27,440
If an engineer asks what the system actually did,

84
00:03:27,440 --> 00:03:29,840
there is a concrete answer there too.

85
00:03:29,840 --> 00:03:32,000
The app is showing both product value

86
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:34,520
and technical accountability in the same screen.

87
00:03:36,800 --> 00:03:38,400
The system is just as explicit

88
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:40,360
when it cannot fix the problem.

89
00:03:40,360 --> 00:03:42,600
Marcus Hale follows the same workflow,

90
00:03:42,600 --> 00:03:45,640
but there is not a qualifying UACR in the chart.

91
00:03:45,640 --> 00:03:46,920
The run ends blocked,

92
00:03:46,920 --> 00:03:48,920
not because the app failed silently,

93
00:03:48,920 --> 00:03:51,720
and not because it tried to bluff its way to success.

94
00:03:51,720 --> 00:03:52,560
It reached the limit

95
00:03:52,560 --> 00:03:54,400
of what it could retrieve automatically,

96
00:03:54,400 --> 00:03:55,760
preserved that decision,

97
00:03:55,760 --> 00:03:58,280
and makes the follow-up state obvious.

98
00:03:58,280 --> 00:04:00,240
That honesty is important.

99
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:02,280
A good demo should show the success path,

100
00:04:02,280 --> 00:04:04,520
but a serious product also has to show

101
00:04:04,520 --> 00:04:06,000
where automation stops.

102
00:04:07,680 --> 00:04:09,160
That's the value here.

103
00:04:09,160 --> 00:04:11,320
Referral intake becomes a deterministic,

104
00:04:11,320 --> 00:04:14,320
inspectable process instead of a black box.

105
00:04:14,320 --> 00:04:15,520
You can show what was submitted,

106
00:04:15,520 --> 00:04:17,200
what was missing, what was repaired,

107
00:04:17,200 --> 00:04:18,920
what still needs manual follow-up,

108
00:04:18,920 --> 00:04:21,920
and when the patient actually became intake-ready.

109
00:04:21,920 --> 00:04:25,480
For a coordinator, that saves time and context switching.

110
00:04:25,480 --> 00:04:27,600
For intake, it improves packet quality

111
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:29,280
without hiding the rules.

112
00:04:29,280 --> 00:04:31,920
And for judges, it proves this is a real product

113
00:04:31,920 --> 00:04:33,640
with real operational behavior.

114
00:04:33,640 --> 00:04:37,280
The impressive part is not just that it reaches accepted.

115
00:04:37,280 --> 00:04:40,000
It is that every state along the way is visible,

116
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:43,560
defensible, and grounded in real product interactions.
